[434|5507] 12:48:25.870 I/NARR-STATE: narrationState → Speaking(segment=NarrationSegment(id=poi_narration_1248733984263505, text=You're standing at the very beginning of America's story as a trading nation. This isn't just a collection of old wharves and buildings; it's the first National Historic Site the United States ever designated, back in 1938. For centuries, ships sailed from these docks to the far corners of the world, bringing back spices, silk, and fortunes that built Salem. Look down at the cobblestones under your feet — they've felt the weight of cargo from the East Indies, and the hurried steps of merchants making deals that shaped a young country. This was a hub of global trade, and a place where fortunes were made and lost. The buildings around you aren't just preserved; they're a reminder of a time when Salem was one of the most important ports in the world. And today, the park also tells a more complete story, acknowledging the role slavery played in building that wealth, and the lives of those who were enslaved. Take a moment to imagine the bustle of activity, the smell of salt air, and the cries of sailors – this waterfront has witnessed it all., type=LONG_NARRATION, poiName=Salem Maritime National Historic Site, voiceId=en-us-x-tpd-local, kind=POI, category=null, refId=poi_narration, isReplay=false)) (autoPlay=true, queueSize=0)
